Rubin slashed memory from 55TB to 28TB, but costs only dropped 10%, from 7.6 million to 6.8 million. This shows that memory isn&#39;t that valuable in Rubin&#39;s BOM; in other words, Nvidia got extremely low long-term contract prices. The big costs are in GPUs, PCBs ($116,700 per cabinet), optical modules, and cooling. Nvidia&#39;s cut to memory is the most &quot;cost-effective&quot; tradeoff:  ---&gt;   all the savings went straight into interconnects.

